st. Three seconds. Maybe four. Then she'd pulled away, mumbled something about her rush, and fled before she could see his face.\\n\\nShe pulls her cart into the usual spot near the arcade entrance, unties the tarp, and begins arranging the display. The morning onigiri gleam under the clear plastic, each one wrapped and labeled. She adjusts the sign, checks her cash box, and takes a breath.\\n\\nHer phone buzzes with notifications—likes and comments flooding the selfie. She glances at the photo: her face flushed and grinning, Brian visible over her shoulder, Jiro smirking in the corner, the oak table and empty ramen bowls framing them. A good photo. A happy photo.\\n\\n*YourCartGirl: omg is that the American chef??*\\n*HiroshimaFoodie: WAIT are you partnering with Nagato Ramen??*\\n*Kenji_Matsuda: congrats Higashi-san!!*\\n\\nShe silences the phone and looks up. Her first customer approaches—a salaryman she's seen a hundred times, reaching for his usual tuna onigiri.\\n\\n\\"One tuna, please,\\" he says.\\n\\nKaho bows, hands him the rice ball, and begins the rhythm of her day.", "type": "text", "state": "done"}]}, {"id": "MrPPXzXWkk04YQsy", "role": "user", "parts": [{"text": "Back at the restaurant, Brian and Jiro are happily bantering through the crazy lunch orders with their small army of chefs buzzing around them. “So… that girl came to see you?” Jiro raises an eyebrow. \\n\\n“Uh… yeah. We met two days ago at her cart. We’re friends now.” He blushes\\n\\nJiro scoffs “Japanese girls do not bring their *friends* onigiri at 7am” and then winks. Brian rolls his eyes and focuses on the next ticket. \\n\\nYou can narrate for Jiro and Kaho, both or one your choice. But do not narrate for Brian.", "type": "text"}]}, {"id": "yl2Z9XRHCXewvTRG", "role": "assistant", "parts": [{"type": "step-start"}, {"text": "The user wants me to continue narrating the story, focusing on Jiro and/or Kaho but not Brian. Let me think about what would be interesting to show.\\n\\nJiro is at the restaurant with Brian, having just teased him about Kaho. The lunch rush is happening. Jiro is a mentor figure, married to a woman who spends his money and complains. He's fond of Brian in a gruff way.\\n\\nKaho is at her cart near the arcade, starting her lunch rush. She's riding high on the morning's events - the partnership offer, eating with the \\"family\\" at Jiro's, the hug with Brian.\\n\\nI could show:\\n1. Jiro observing Brian, thinking about the situation, maybe his own marriage\\n2. Kaho during her lunch rush, thinking about everything\\n3. Both in parallel\\n\\nLet me go with both, showing parallel moments. Kaho during her rush, and Jiro at the restaurant. This gives good contrast and shows both characters developing.\\n\\nFor Kaho - she's dealing with customers, thinking about Brian, the partnership, her future. Maybe a moment where she has to focus despite her racing thoughts.\\n\\nFor Jiro - he's watching Brian, maybe reflecting on his own situation, thinking about the partnership with Kaho's business.", "type": "reasoning", "state": "done", "providerMetadata": {"openrouter": {"reasoning_details": [{"text": "The user wants me to continue narrating the story, focusing on Jiro and/or Kaho but not Brian. Let me think about what would be interesting to show.\\n\\nJiro is at the restaurant with Brian, having just teased him about Kaho. The lunch rush is happening. Jiro is a mentor figure, married to a woman who spends his money and complains. He's fond of Brian in a gruff way.\\n\\nKaho is at her cart near the arcade, starting her lunch rush. She's riding high on the morning's events - the partnership offer, eating with the \\"family\\" at Jiro's, the hug with Brian.\\n\\nI could show:\\n1. Jiro observing Brian, thinking about the situation, maybe his own marriage\\n2. Kaho during her lunch rush, thinking about everything\\n3. Both in parallel\\n\\nLet me go with both, showing parallel moments. Kaho during her rush, and Jiro at the restaurant. This gives good contrast and shows both characters developing.\\n\\nFor Kaho - she's dealing with customers, thinking about Brian, the partnership, her future. Maybe a moment where she has to focus despite her racing thoughts.\\n\\nFor Jiro - he's watching Brian, maybe reflecting on his own situation, thinking about the partnership with Kaho's business.", "type": "reasoning.text", "index": 0, "format": "unknown"}]}}}, {"text": "Jiro watches Brian fumble through the next ticket—hands steady on the noodles but that faraway look in his eyes. The boy is gone. Completely useless. Jiro has seen this before in young chefs, the distraction of a pretty face, the slow descent into lovesick stupidity. He should be annoyed. Instead, he feels something like fondness.\\n\\n\\"Focus, Devereaux,\\" he barks, though not unkindly. \\"Women don't like men who overcook their noodles.\\"\\n\\nHe turns back to his own station, stirring broth he's made ten thousand times. His wife texted him earlier—another complaint about the credit card bill, another demand for a vacation he's too busy to take. Twenty-three years of marriage and she still doesn't understand that the restaurant is not a job. It's a heartbeat. It's the only thing that's ever been truly his.\\n\\nHe glances at Brian again. The American has a chance at something real. Something fresh. Jiro won't stand in the way of that.\\n\\n---\\n\\nKaho's hands move automatically—wrap, hand, bow, receive payment, repeat. The line stretches six people deep. The arcade chimes and beeps behind her. A group of high school girls giggle over their phones, probably looking at her selfie.\\n\\n\\"That's her,\\" one whispers. \\"The cart girl.\\"\\n\\nKaho pretends not to hear. She focuses on the salmon onigiri in her hands, the warmth of the rice through the nori, the weight of the morning still settling in her chest. A partnership. A family. A man who blushes when she hugs him.\\n\\nShe wraps another onigiri and smiles.", "type": "text", "state": "done"}]}, {"id": "4kaT4EDUAU16INzU", "role": "user", "parts": [{"text": "The girls approach Kaho. “Higashi-samaaa” one calls shyly. “Can we have a selfie with you?” Another blushes “we want to make onigiri some day just like you. It’s so good!”", "type": "text"}]}, {"id": "0I2AhZVtgT03IHFp", "role": "assistant", "parts": [{"type": "step-start"}, {"text": "The user wants me to narrate Kaho's interaction with the high school girls who are fans of her work. This is a sweet moment of recognition and connection with her followers. I should show Kaho's warmth with customers, her modesty about her fame, and the genuine connection she has with her community.\\n\\nLet me write this scene showing:\\n- The girls' excitement and admiration\\n- Kaho's humble, warm response\\n- Maybe some practical advice about making onigiri\\n- Her growing comfort with her small local fame\\n\\nI should keep it to 3-5 paragraphs, present tense, and not write for Brian since he's not present in this scene.", "type": "reasoning", "state": "done", "providerMetadata": {"openrouter": {"reasoning_details": [{"text": "The user wants me to narrate Kaho's interaction with the high school girls who are fans of her work. This is a sweet moment of recognition and connection with her followers. I should show Kaho's warmth with customers, her modesty about her fame, and the genuine connection she has with her community.\\n\\nLet me write this scene showing:\\n- The girls' excitement and admiration\\n- Kaho's humble, warm response\\n- Maybe some practical advice about making onigiri\\n- Her growing comfort with her small local fame\\n\\nI should keep it to 3-5 paragraphs, present tense, and not write for Brian since he's not present in this scene.", "type": "reasoning.text", "index": 0, "format": "unknown"}]}}}, {"text": "Kaho blinks, startled. Selfie? With her? She's had customers recognize her before—a few comments on her posts, the occasional regular who follows her cart location. But this feels different. These girls look at her like she's someone worth looking up to.\\n\\n\\"Of course,\\" she says, warmth spreading across her face. She steps out from behind the cart, wiping her hands on her apron. \\"But no -sama, okay? Just Kaho-san. Or Kaho-chan.\\" She laughs softly. \\"I'm not that old yet.\\"\\n\\nThe girls cluster around her, holding up their phones. Kaho ducks into the frame, making a small peace sign. The shutter clicks. They squeal and thank her, bowing repeatedly.\\n\\n\\"Onigiri is not so hard,\\" Kaho says, moving back to her cart. \\"Warm hands. Good rice. Don't press too hard—let the rice keep its shape.\\" She demonstrates with a fresh salmon onigiri, her palms cradling it gently. \\"Like holding something precious. Not too tight, not too loose.\\"\\n\\nThe girls watch with wide eyes. One scribbles notes in a tiny notebook.\\n\\n\\"Practice every day,\\" Kaho adds, pressing the nori into place. \\"That's the real secret. Your hands have to remember.\\"\\n\\nShe hands them each a plum onigiri, free of charge. \\"For studying. Good luck.\\"\\n\\nThey bow again, clutching the onigiri like treasure. Kaho watches them go, something warm and unfamiliar settling in her chest. Not just a cart girl anymore. Something more.", "type": "text", "state": "done"}]}, {"id": "t0u3poRIwOAwSnFg", "role": "user", "parts": [{"text": "Rewrite that, she is actually used to being recognized and asked for selfies, she’s very popular on social media in Japan", "type": "text"}]}, {"id": "PlCR2tE8c57BQAYl", "role": "assistant", "parts": [{"type": "step-start"}, {"text": "The user wants me to rewrite the scene where the high school girls approach Kaho. They've pointed out that Kaho is actually used to being recognized and asked for selfies - she's popular on social media in Japan. So I should rewrite it with Kaho being more confident and accustomed to this kind of attention, rather than being startled and surprised by it.", "type": "reasoning", "state": "done", "providerMetadata": {"openrouter": {"reasoning_details": [{"text": "The user wants me to rewrite the scene where the high school girls approach Kaho. They've pointed out that Kaho is actually used to being recognized and asked for selfies - she's popular on social media in Japan. So I should rewrite it with Kaho being more confident and accustomed to this kind of attention, rather than being startled and surprised by it.", "type": "reasoning.text", "index": 0, "format": "unknown"}]}}}, {"text": "Kaho smiles and steps out from behind the cart with practiced ease. This happens most days now—ever since her following crossed ten thousand, then twenty, then more. She's learned the rhythm of it: the shy approach, the request, the quick pose, the small gift of an onigiri tucked into their hands as thanks.\\n\\n\\"Of course,\\" she says, adjusting her apron. \\"Come, come.\\"\\n\\nThe girls cluster around her, phones already positioned. Kaho tilts her head, makes a peace sign with her free hand. The shutter clicks twice, three times. She checks the frame, suggests one more with better lighting, and they squeal their approval.\\n\\n\\"Onigiri is easy,\\" she says, returning to her station. \\"Warm hands. Good rice. Don't press too hard—let it keep its shape.\\" She demonstrates with practiced grace, her palms cradling the rice like something precious. \\"Like this. Not too tight, not too loose.\\"\\n\\nThe girl with the notebook scribbles furiously. Kaho recognizes the type—serious, determined, maybe dreaming of a kitchen of her own someday.\\n\\nShe hands each of them a plum onigiri. \\"For studying. Come back and tell me how yours turn out.\\"\\n\\nThey bow and scatter, already posting. Kaho's phone buzzes with tags. She glances at the notifications—her engagement numbers climbing, new followers, the selfie already circulating—then silences it. The line has grown again. Back to work.", "type": "text", "state": "done"}]}, {"id": "noen3uOGM8LQbLrl", "role": "user", "parts": [{"text": "By 1pm she